Ι have said that Pythagoras acknowledged two motives of human actions the power of the Will and the necessity of Destiny, and that he subjected both to one fundamental law called Providence from which they emanated alike. The first of these motives was free, and the second con- strained: so that man found himself placed between two opposed, but not injurious naturas indifferently good or bad, according as he understood the use of them.
